title: For Sale:  Adams Arms complete factory upper receiver
postcontent:
unfired in box. no drama, this isn't a firearm. cash and carry.

Product Information
This Adams Arms AR-15 A3 Base Mid Gas Piston Upper Assembly is chambered in 5.56x45mm NATO and comes ready to fire right out of the box after installation onto any standard AR-15 lower receiver. This Base Mid upper comes equipped with a 16" melonite-finished barrel, A2 flash hider, bolt carrier group, charging handle, picatinny rail gas block, delta ring assembly and a set of polymer 2-piece handguards. Additional features include a forged A3 flat-top configuration that's ready to accept the shooter's choice of optic and/or rear iron sight, M4 feed ramps to help ensure reliable feeding and functioning during rapid strings of fire, and a mid length gas system for a smoother recoil impulse and longer sight radius.

The upper's barrel has been finished inside and out with Adams Arms' proprietary QPQ Melonite treatment that bonds with the metal on a molecular level. Also referred to as salt bath nitriding, this treatment produces an extremely hard, slick surface on steel that resists carbon adhesion and increases corrosion resistance, extending a barrel's service life by reducing the friction produced inside the bore upon firing for a net decrease in bore surface wear over time. Nitriding converts the barrel steel's surface without any build-up, retaining all of the benefits of traditional chrome lining without suffering the accuracy degradation commonly encountered with it due to the uneven application of chrome inside the barrel's bore. The end result is a barrel that's capable of producing accuracy on par with a match stainless steel tube, while also exhibiting the longevity and resilience of a chrome lined, mil-spec barrel.

All Adams Arms uppers feature a short stroke gas piston operating system, which prevents hot gas and debris from being directed back into the action upon firing. The result is a rifle that runs cooler, cleaner and more reliably than those utilizing a standard direct gas impingement system of operation. To ensure that damage doesn't occur to the buffer tube from carrier tilt, the bolt carrier is equipped with enlarged "skis" to help guide it into the receiver extension. The bolt carrier's solid steel, 1-piece construction incorporates an integral piston strike face to guarantee integrity over time, while the bolt assembly is spring loaded for proper lock-up and to help reduce bolt bounce and cam pin wear. All piston components are finished in QPQ Melonite for corrosion resistance and easy cleaning/maintenance.

title: For Sale:  #4251 Marlin 1881 rifle, OBFMCBw/DSTs, 45/70 with VG++ bore
postcontent: #4251 Marlin 1881 rifle, OBFMCBw/DSTs, 45/70 with VG++ bore and strong tight action. Very early 14XX serial number (circa 1882 manufacture). These big top-ejecting Marlins were the first serious competitors to Winchesters dynasty and caused Winchester to scramble to get John Browning to develop the Model 1886 and basically to stop promoting the Model 1876. The Burgess patented 28” barreled Marlin was clearly a superior rifle as compared to the 1876. and was also capable of using the very popular 45Govt cartridge (45/70) which was too long of a case for the ’76. Overall a thin brownish patina on smooth metal with some plumming blue on the barrel. Unusual rear barrel sight (…no doubt a period replacemet, and if objectionable, I’ll replace it with a generic buck-horn Sporting sight. Handsome and very impressive rifle! VG as described

postcontent:
For sale is my Colt Gold Cup Trophy 1911 .22LR pistol with approximately 300 rounds of ammunition included (what's left of a brick of Remington Golden hollowpoints).  This pistol is manufactured in Germany by Walther under Colt license, and imported by Umarex (Walther's parent company).  I bought this pistol about six months ago and I've fired a couple thousand rounds through it, which is like nothing for a .22 pistol.  This pistol is smooth-shooting, accurate, and reliable.  I've done some light modification to it, but I still have all the original parts to include with it, so that you can change it back to its original state if you wanted to.  I've fitted a Greider Precision short aluminum match trigger, installed a Chip McCormick polymer checkered mainspring housing, installed a factory Umarex/Walther extended thumb safety, and installed a set of factory Colt cocobolo checkered wood grips.  I also have an extra factory Umarex/Walther recoil spring for it.  The pistol comes with one 12rd magazine, the same as if purchased new at a retail store.

I prefer the Colt/Walther/Umarex series of 1911 .22LR pistols because they disassemble just like a standard Colt 1911 .45ACP with no tools needed.  The other brands of 1911 .22LR pistols require tools for field stripping.

If the buyer of my pistol is interested, I also have four additional factory 12rd magazines available for sale, otherwise I'll sell them separately after my pistol is sold.  The mags are about impossible to find right now (high demand), and market price is up to $50 each.  I'll sell them to my pistol buyer for $35 each.  I also have over 2000 rounds of .22LR ammo that I'll offer first to the buyer of my pistol.

title: For Sale:  FN FNH five-seven, with 6 mags and 250 rounds of 5.7x28
postcontent:
This FN Five-seven pistol is in great condition, fired <150 rounds thru; rarely carried, this pistol is near new in the box with all accessories, and a total of SIX high capacity 20-RD magazines plus 250 rounds of 5.7x28 40 grain VMax ammo. Zero holster wear - no holster. Comes as a package ready to go with original box, papers, org. test-shot cartridge, tools, and six (6) 20-round magazines. One sealed box of 50 cartridges (Ball-SS192) plus 20 rounds and two Kydex holsters included.

The Five-seven is extremely lightweight for a full-size gun, weighing ~ 1.5 lbs with a fully-loaded 20-round magazine and one in the chamber... that's twenty-one rounds; and yet two 20-round mags to go. The Five-seven launches a 40 grain bullet with a screaming super-accurate Muzzle Velocity of 2,350 fps and a Muzzle Energy of 390 ft. lbs. Not bad for a gun that has a kick that feels like a little cricket in your palm, and way, way, fun to shoot.

As stated, in addition to the ammo, two high-quality Kydex holsters are included. Both great for concealed carry: 1) Blade-Tech Inside-the-Waistband (IWB) Holster with pair of IWB snap loops, and two J-hooks (1.25" & 1.5") sets; 2) Fobus Evolution Roto-Holster™ Paddle, rotates 360° employing a forward or rearward cant.

The Five-seven is a full-size pistol, having an overall length of 208 mm (8.2 in), a height of 137 mm (5.4 in), and a max width of 36 mm (1.4 in). It has the same grip angle as the distinguished Browning Hi-Power and M1911 pistols. The Five-seven barrel is cold hammer-forged and chrome-lined, with a total length of 122 mm (4.8 in) and a rifled length of 94 mm (3.7 in). The barrel has eight rifling grooves with a right-hand twist rate of 1:231 mm (1:9.1 in), and it weighs 113 g (0.25 lb). It has a stated service life of 20,000 rounds and the Five-seven is noted for being very accurate. 

Current models of the Five-seven are single-action, having a short and light trigger pull of 2 to 3 daN (4.4 to 6.6 lbF). They have a Picatinny rail for mounting accessories, and a magazine safety mechanism that prevents the pistol from firing without a magazine inserted.

Shipping will be from my FFL to your FFL, $30 for shipping within US.
